<h2>3. Mailchimp -- Best for Absolute Beginners</h2>

Mailchimp is the most recognized name in email marketing and the most beginner-friendly platform. The drag-and-drop editor is excellent, templates are plentiful, and the learning curve is minimal.

The catch: deliverability is noticeably worse than ConvertKit or AWeber, automation is limited on the free tier, and pricing gets expensive quickly as your list grows.

For operators serious about email as a revenue channel, Mailchimp's deliverability limitations are a real problem. You're fighting for inbox placement on infrastructure shared with a massive volume of other senders, including many with poor list hygiene.

<p><strong>Deliverability:</strong> Below average for the industry.</p>

<p><strong>Automation:</strong> Limited on free, functional on paid.</p>

<p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Free to 500 contacts, $13/mo for Essentials.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Absolute beginners who prioritize ease of use over performance.</p>

<h2>4. ActiveCampaign -- Best for Complex Automation</h2>

ActiveCampaign has the most powerful automation engine in the mid-market email space. If your workflows are genuinely complex -- multiple conditional branches, CRM integration, lead scoring, site tracking -- ActiveCampaign handles it better than any platform at this price point.

The tradeoff is complexity. ActiveCampaign has a steep learning curve and takes significant time to set up properly. For most operators, the automation depth is overkill -- GoHighLevel handles multi-channel automation better for operator-specific workflows.

<p><strong>Deliverability:</strong> Good.</p>

<p><strong>Automation:</strong> Best in class for email-specific complexity.</p>

<p><strong>Pricing:</strong> $15/mo starting, no free tier.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Operators with genuinely complex email automation requirements who don't need SMS or other channels.</p>

